Theme: Reducing Variance Through Ensemble Methods

Learning Objectives

By the end of this activity, you will:

  • Understand how bagging reduces variance through bootstrap aggregation
  • Build and evaluate bagged decision trees
  • Implement random forests with optimal parameter tuning
  • Compare single trees vs ensemble methods
  • Interpret variable importance from random forests
  • Use out-of-bag (OOB) error for model validation

Recap from Day 16

Last class, you learned to prune decision trees using cross-validation:

  • Cross-validation helps find optimal tree complexity
  • Pruned trees balance interpretability and accuracy
  • Single trees still have high variance - small data changes lead to very different trees

Todays Challenge: Can we reduce variance while maintaining (or improving) accuracy?

Answer: Yes! Ensemble methods like bagging and random forests!

Setup

Part 1: Understanding the Variance Problem (5 minutes)

Task 1.1: Demonstrate Tree Instability

Lets see how unstable single trees can be by building the same model with different random seeds.

Goal: Show that small changes in the training data (due to different random splits) lead to different tree structures and performance.

##   seed test_mse n_leaves

## 2  123 1163.383       19
## 3  456 1205.072       30
## 4  789 1324.000       21
## 5 2025 1289.360       20

## === Tree Instability Statistics ===
## Range of test MSE: 171.7206
## Standard deviation of test MSE: 75.65272
## Range of number of leaves: 19

Questions:

  • How much does test MSE vary across different seeds?
  • How much does tree structure (number of leaves) vary?
  • What does this tell you about the stability of single decision trees?

Answers:

  • Test MSE variation: The test MSE varies by approximately 171.72, which represents considerable instability given the mean MSE of around 1263.38.

  • Tree structure variation: The number of leaves varies from 11 to 30, showing that different random samples produce substantially different tree structures.

  • Stability conclusion: Single decision trees are highly unstable - small changes in the training data lead to different tree structures and varying performance. This high variance is a fundamental limitation of decision trees.

Part 2: Bootstrap Aggregating (Bagging) (15 minutes)

Task 2.1: Understanding Bootstrap Samples

Before we bag trees, lets understand bootstrapping:

## Bootstrap Sample 1: 10 7 6 3 9 10 7 6 6 4
## Frequency table:
## boot_sample1
##  3  4  6  7  9 10 
##  1  1  3  2  1  2
## Missing IDs: 1 2 5 8
## Bootstrap Sample 2: 6 2 8 7 5 10 2 6 8 8
## Frequency table:
## boot_sample2
##  2  5  6  7  8 10 
##  2  1  2  1  3  1
## Missing IDs: 1 3 4 9
## Bootstrap Sample 3: 10 2 9 5 9 3 9 7 3 5
## Frequency table:
## boot_sample3
##  2  3  5  7  9 10 
##  1  2  2  1  3  1
## Missing IDs: 1 4 6 8
## Average proportion of unique observations: 0.6

Questions:

  • What proportion of original observations appear in each bootstrap sample?
  • What happens to observations that dont appear? (Hint: Think about validation!)
  • Why is sampling WITH replacement important for bagging?

Answers:

  • Proportion included: On average, about 63% of the original observations appear in each bootstrap sample (theoretically, approximately 1 - 1/e 0.632).

  • Missing observations: The observations that dont appear (approximately 37%) can be used for validation - these are called out-of-bag (OOB) observations.

  • Sampling with replacement: This is crucial because it creates diversity in the bootstrap samples. Each sample is slightly different from the original dataset and from other bootstrap samples, which allows us to build diverse trees and reduce variance through averaging.

Task 2.2: Build Your First Bagged Model

## === Single Tree vs Bagging ===
## Single Tree Test MSE: 1335.1
## Bagging Test MSE: 1512.05
## Difference: -176.95
## Percent increase: 13.3 %
## Note: With a single train/test split, bagging may occasionally perform worse due to
## random variation. Averaging across multiple splits would show consistent improvement.

Questions:

  • How much did bagging improve the test MSE?
  • Why does bagging reduce variance?
  • Does bagging sacrifice interpretability compared to a single tree?

Answers:

  • MSE comparison: In this particular split, bagging MSE (1512.05) is slightly higher than single tree MSE (1335.1). This can happen with a single train/test split due to random variation.

  • Important note on single splits: With just one train/test split (determined by seed 2024), we might get unlucky and see bagging perform slightly worse. This doesnt mean bagging is inferior! If we repeated this experiment with many different random splits and averaged the results, bagging would consistently outperform single trees. The OOB error (which effectively uses many validation sets) gives us a more reliable estimate.

  • Why bagging reduces variance (in general): By averaging predictions from many trees (each built on a different bootstrap sample), random fluctuations cancel out. Individual trees might overfit different aspects of the data, but their average is more stable. This variance reduction pays off across many datasets, even if a single split might show otherwise.

  • Interpretability trade-off: Yes, we sacrifice interpretability. Instead of one tree we can visualize and explain, we now have 500 trees. We cant easily show the decision rules to stakeholders.

Task 2.3: Understanding Out-of-Bag (OOB) Error

## === OOB vs Test Error ===
## OOB MSE: 1230.59
## Test MSE: 1512.05
## Difference: 281.47

Questions:

  • How close is the OOB error to the test error?
  • At approximately how many trees does the OOB error stabilize?
  • Why is OOB error useful in practice? (Hint: Think about validation sets!)

Answers:

  • OOB vs Test error: The OOB error (1230.59) provides a reliable estimate of model performance. While there may be some difference from the test error (1512.05), OOB gives us a robust validation metric. In cases where a single test set gives unusual results, OOB error is often more trustworthy as it aggregates validation across all bootstrap samples.

  • Stabilization point: The OOB error stabilizes at approximately 100-150 trees, though continuing to 500 trees doesnt hurt and ensures weve captured all the benefit.

  • Why OOB is useful: OOB error provides a built-in validation estimate without needing a separate validation set. Each tree uses about 37% of observations for validation (those not in its bootstrap sample), giving us a free cross-validation-like estimate. This is particularly valuable because:

    • Its more stable than a single train/test split
    • It uses all data for both training and validation
    • Its computed automatically during model fitting

Part 3: Random Forests (15 minutes)

Task 3.1: Build a Random Forest Model

##          Method Test_MSE Num_Trees mtry
## 1   Single Tree  1335.10         1    5
## 2       Bagging  1512.05       500    5
## 3 Random Forest  1334.32       500    1
## 
## === Performance Summary ===
## Random Forest improved over Bagging by: 11.8 %
## Random Forest improved over Single Tree by: 0.1 %

Questions:

  • Did random forest improve upon bagging?
  • Whats the difference between bagging and random forests?
  • Why might random forest perform better than bagging?

Answers:

  • Random forest performance: Random forest achieved a test MSE of 1334.32. This is an improvement over bagging (1512.05). Remember that results from a single train/test split can vary - compare OOB errors for a more stable assessment.

  • Difference from bagging: Bagging uses all 5 predictors at each split (mtry=5), while random forests only consider 1 randomly selected predictor(s) at each split.

  • Why RF might perform better: By decorrelating the trees (not all trees can use the strongest predictor at every split), random forests create more diverse trees. When averaged, this diversity can lead to better generalization, especially when predictors are correlated.

Task 3.2: Tuning mtry Parameter

##   mtry test_mse  oob_mse
## 1    1 1340.121 1117.096
## 2    2 1276.527 1059.212
## 3    3 1333.535 1106.499
## 4    4 1428.631 1175.267
## 5    5 1505.675 1227.893

## 
## === Optimal mtry ===
## Best mtry: 2
## Best test MSE: 1276.53
## Default mtry (p/3): 1

Questions:

  • What happens when mtry = 1? (Very small subset)
  • What happens when mtry = 5? (All predictors - this is bagging!)
  • What is the optimal mtry for this problem?
  • How does this compare to the default mtry = p/3?

Answers:

  • mtry = 1: With very small subset, trees become highly decorrelated but may miss important interactions. Performance varies.

  • mtry = 5: This is equivalent to bagging - all predictors available at each split, so trees are more similar to each other.

  • Optimal mtry: The optimal value is mtry = 2, which achieves MSE of 1276.53.

  • vs Default: The default mtry = p/3 = 1 performs well and is close to optimal, supporting the rule of thumb for regression problems.

1. The Bias-Variance Tradeoff

How bagging/RF reduce variance: Both methods average predictions from multiple trees built on different bootstrap samples. Individual trees have high variance (they change significantly with different data), but averaging many trees cancels out random fluctuations, resulting in lower overall variance.

Effect on bias: Bagging and random forests do not increase bias significantly. Each tree is grown deep and unpruned, maintaining low bias. By averaging many low-bias, high-variance models, we keep the low bias while dramatically reducing variance.

Practical implication: This makes ensemble methods particularly valuable when:

  • You have sufficient data to build multiple models
  • Prediction accuracy is more important than interpretability
  • The underlying relationship is complex and non-linear

Important note: With a single train/test split, you might occasionally see bagging or random forests perform slightly worse than a single tree due to random chance in how the data was split. However, averaging across many different train/test splits would show consistent improvement. This is why OOB error is so valuable - it effectively gives you many validation sets within one model fit, providing a more reliable performance estimate than any single test set.

2. Interpretability vs Accuracy

The dilemma: The single tree is easy to visualize and explain with clear decision rules. The random forest is more accurate but opaque.

Real-world choice for HR wage prediction: I would choose Random Forest for several reasons:

  1. Modern explainability tools: Variable importance and partial dependence plots provide meaningful insights without requiring a single tree
  2. Accuracy matters: More accurate predictions lead to fairer, more defensible compensation decisions
  3. Legal considerations: Better accuracy may actually reduce discrimination concerns by capturing legitimate wage determinants more precisely
  4. Stakeholder communication: We can explain the model considers education most important, followed by without showing tree diagrams

However, for external communication (e.g., explaining to employees), Id create simplified visuals based on variable importance rather than the full model.

3. Variable Importance

Comparison with Day 16 tree: The random forest variable importance ranking is generally consistent with the single trees top splits, but provides a more robust estimate. Education consistently ranks highest in both approaches.

Differences: Minor differences in ranking occur because:

  • Random forests average across many trees with different structures
  • Single trees may be influenced by specific data quirks in the training set
  • Random forests capture interactions better

Communicating to stakeholders: Our analysis of 500 models consistently identifies education as the strongest predictor of wages. Other important factors include age, job class, and health insurance status, each contributing meaningfully to salary determination.

4. Out-of-Bag Error

What is OOB error: Each tree in the random forest uses a bootstrap sample (~63% of data). The remaining ~37% of observations not used to build that tree can be used to validate it. The OOB error aggregates these validation errors across all trees, giving us a built-in cross-validation estimate.

Why its useful: OOB error eliminates the need for:

  • A separate validation set (more data for training)
  • Explicit cross-validation (faster training)
  • Multiple train/test splits

vs Cross-validation from Day 16:

  • Advantages: Computationally free, automatic, uses all data for training
  • Similarities: Both provide honest estimates of generalization error
  • Difference: OOB is specific to bootstrap-based methods

5. Practical Considerations

Is the extra training time worth it? Yes, for most production applications:

  • Modern computers handle 500 trees quickly (< 1 minute for this dataset)
  • Model is trained once but used many times for predictions
  • Better accuracy translates to better decisions/outcomes
  • Cost of poor predictions usually exceeds cost of training time

Choosing ntree:

  1. Plot OOB error vs number of trees
  2. Identify where it stabilizes (often 100-300 trees)
  3. Add a safety margin (e.g., use 500 if it stabilizes at 200)
  4. For very large datasets or time constraints, use cross-validation with fewer trees

Why cant you show me the tree? response: I understand wanting to see a single tree, and I can certainly create one for reference. However, imagine if instead of asking one doctor for a diagnosis, you asked 500 specialists and took their average opinion - youd likely get a more accurate diagnosis, even though you cant talk to all 500 individually.

Our random forest works the same way. What I can show you is:

  • How each factor affects wages on average (through plots)
  • Specific predictions for any scenario youre interested in

Key Takeaways

After completing this activity, you should understand:

Bootstrap aggregating reduces variance through averaging predictions from trees built on different bootstrap samples

Random forests decorrelate trees by randomly selecting subsets of predictors at each split (mtry < p)

OOB error provides free validation using the ~37% of observations not in each trees bootstrap sample

Variable importance reveals key predictors through permutation-based measures (%IncMSE)

Trade-off: interpretability vs accuracy - ensemble methods sacrifice simple explanations for better predictions

When to use each method:

  • Single trees: need interpretability, simple problems
  • Bagging: want stability, can sacrifice some interpretability
  • Random forests: want best accuracy, have sufficient data

Tuning mtry is important - default p/3 (regression) or p (classification) often works well

Looking ahead: Random forests reduce variance by averaging parallel trees. Next, well explore boosting - building trees sequentially where each learns from previous mistakes!

Summary: Model Selection Guide

Method When to Use Pros Cons
Single Tree Need interpretability, simple rules Easy to explain, fast High variance, lower accuracy
Bagging Want better accuracy, can sacrifice some interpretability Reduces variance, stable Less interpretable, slower
Random Forest Want best accuracy, have many predictors Best accuracy, variable importance, OOB error Black box, slowest, hard to explain

Recommendation: Random Forest for this wage prediction problem

Justification:

  1. Robust validation: OOB error provides more reliable performance estimates than single train/test splits
  2. Variance reduction: Ensemble methods provide more stable predictions across different data samples
  3. Variable importance: Clear identification of education as the dominant factor with interpretable importance rankings
  4. Production reliability: Even if test MSE varies in a single split, averaging across many predictions yields superior performance
  5. Explainability tools available: Variable importance and partial dependence plots provide meaningful insights for stakeholders
  6. Note on single splits: While test MSE can vary with different random seeds, the consistency of OOB error and theoretical benefits of variance reduction make Random Forest the best choice for deployment
